INSERT INTO `blogs` VALUES (1,'Hosting a Node.js HTTP Server on a Raspberry Pi','Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consete tur sadipscing elitr, sed diam nonumy eirmod tempor invidunt','hosting-a-nodejs-http-server-on-a-raspberry-pi','2021-04-28','The Raspberry Pi is a great tool for running your own mini server from home. If You have multiple Pi\'s you are also able to experiment with mass distribution, and balance loaders. However fun those may be, you will first need a running server on your Pi. I will try my best to walk you through the process. Just follow these steps:\n\n**Set up your Raspberry Pi**\n\nTo get started you will need the Raspbian operating system installed on your Pi. The process of burning the os image onto your sd card is thoroughly explained in their [Getting Started Guide](https://www.raspberrypi.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/quick-start-guide-v2_1.pdf). You will also need the Pi connected to your modem via an ethernet cable or wireless dongle.\n\n**Open up some ports**\n\nOur web server will be hosted on port 8080 and we must therefore open traffic to that port. Anyone accessing our external ip address under that port will be forwarded to our devices ip address.\n\nThe important ports to open are:\n\n- Port 22 for SSH - with extra precautions\n- Port 21 for FTP - with extra precautions\n- Port 8080 for our web server traffic. You can use any port over > 1024.\n\nIf you wish your website not to require a port in the address simply pre-route all traffic from 8080 to port 80 with the following command:\n\n```$ sudo iptables -A PREROUTING -t nat -p tcp --dport 80 -j REDIRECT --to-port 8080```\n\nThis needs to be re-run each time you reboot your Pi. Add the line to the \'/etc/rc.local\' file.\n\n**Wirelessly connect to your Pi (Optional)**\n\nIf you wish to wirelessly manage your Pi you will need to establish a secure shell(SSH) connection with it. To do this you will require the Pi\'s local ip address. This can be found in your modem\'s connected devices page, or through the following terminal command:\n\n```$ ifconfig```\n\nOnce that is done, connect via your pc on the same network with an ssh client. Use PuTTY if you\'re on windows, or this terminal command if on Linux/Mac:\n\n```$ ssh piUsername@192.168.x.x```\n\nBoth these methods will require your Pi\'s password. If they don\'t then you need to set one right now! No password protection will result in anybody being able to connect to your server!\n\n**Installing Node.js**\n\nYou can now Install node with the following terminal commands:\n\n```$ curl -sL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_6.x | sudo -E bash -```\n\n```$ sudo apt-get install -y nodejs```\n\n**Upload a simple web application to your Pi**\n\nYou can upload any web application you may have to your raspberry Pi. An easy way to do this is via FTP or SSHFS which will allow for easy drag and dropping. Here is a simple express app I uploaded for demo purposes:\n\n```\nvar express = require(\'express\');\nvar app = express();\n\napp.get(\'/\', function (req, res) {\n  res.send(\'Hello World!\');\n});\n\nvar server = app.listen(8080, function () {\n  var host = server.address().address;\n  var port = server.address().port;\n\n  console.log(\'Example app listening at http://%s:%s\', host, port);\n});\n```\n**Run it with node**\n\nStart up your web application with node like so:\n\n```$ node app.js```\n\nOnce started you may visit the application on you local network by visiting [http://192.168.x.x:port/](http://192.168.x.xport). To visit it from outside your network you will need your external ip address.  Getting your external ip address is as easy as visiting [IPChicken](http://ipchicken.com).\n\n**Important note:**\n\nYou cannot visit the site via your external domain if you are on the same network. If on the same network, use the local address. If you want to test that the external ip is correctly routing to your Pi server use your cellphone data, or another wifi connection. Another important thing to know is that your ISP is likely not giving you a static ip address. This means that your site will change IP\'s once in a while. Look into dynamic dns, or getting a static ip.\n\n**Next steps**\n\nYou have a very basic nodeJS http server running on your Pi. You may now look to expand on that with some extra cool and secure features such as the following:\n\n- Domains/Subdomains! These are nice to have. [DOT.tk](http://dot.tk) offers free .tk domains. Great for development\n- DDos protection. Look into providers, as you probably wouldn\'t want your bandwidth stolen.\n- MongoDB/MySQL Why not host a database on your Pi?\n\nThat\'s all folks! If you have any questions ask in the comment section below, and I will get back to you as soon as possible.',1,1,'2021-04-22 09:34:13','2021-05-02 08:22:35'),(2,'How To Solve Design Problem Within Few Hours','Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consete tur sadipscing elitr, sed diam nonumy eirmod tempor invidunt','how-to-solve-design-problem-within-few-hours','2021-11-12','I\'m baby direct trade gastropub vape, pork belly migas you probably haven\'t heard of them freegan shaman kombucha pitchfork marfa 90\'s prism offal. Swag gluten-free readymade typewriter irony lyft 8-bit kitsch. Beard man braid direct trade taiyaki lumbersexual celiac meggings forage. Green juice four loko readymade meditation bushwick trust fund. Next level ugh intelligentsia hammock, man braid taiyaki chartreuse chia authentic williamsburg raclette 90\'s iceland.\n\nWolf ugh twee post-ironic. Mixtape selfies adaptogen coloring book mlkshk, hexagon seitan poutine bushwick cold-pressed. Cred cray actually truffaut intelligentsia jean shorts tattooed pug artisan helvetica biodiesel snackwave bushwick keytar messenger bag. Banh mi cornhole crucifix keffiyeh. Flexitarian franzen edison bulb, helvetica humblebrag pug fanny pack brooklyn everyday carry enamel pin messenger bag subway tile trust fund ennui.\n\nRamps stumptown farm-to-table chillwave occupy. Vexillologist ac